193","1290":"1290","1191":"1191","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","about 1189":"circa 1189","North Meols, Lancashire, England":"North Meols, Lancashire, England","Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England","Winwick, Cheshire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1185–":"1185–Deceased","1185–Male":"1185–Deceased","1191–1269":"1191–1269","1193–1258":"1193–1258","1166–Female":"1166–Deceased","1210–1246":"1210–1246","1165–1215":"1165–1215","–1215":"–1215","1187":"1210","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1290":"1290","1191":"1191","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","about 1189":"about 1189","North Meols, Lancashire, England":"North Meols, Lancashire, England","Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England","Winwick, Cheshire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Winwick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Winnick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Winnick","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer.","English: habitational name from any of the three places called Winwick in Huntingdonshire, Lancashire, and Northamptonshire. The Huntingdonshire and Northamptonshire placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wina</i> + Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farmstead’. The Lancashire placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Wineca</i> + Old English <i>wīc</i>.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of <b>Winnik</b>, an occupational name for a wine seller, from Polish <i>wino</i> ‘wine’ + the agent suffix <i>-nik</i>."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":30,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":39,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":74,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":105,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh de Winwick was born in 1185, in Winwick, Lancashire, England as the son of Sir William de Wynwick and Matilda Thornton. He had at least 1 daughter with Wife of Hugh de Winwick."},"et":{"1185–":"1185–Surnud","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1191–1269":"1191–1269","1193–1258":"1193–1258","1166–Female":"1166–Surnud","1210–1246":"1210–1246","1165–1215":"1165–1215","–1215":"–1215","1187":"1210","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1290":"1290","1191":"1191","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","about 1189":"umbes 1189","North Meols, Lancashire, England":"North Meols, Lancashire, England","Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England","Winwick, Cheshire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1185–":"1185–Kuollut","1185